Part 10

The new plant at Nandyal sat on twelve acres of former cotton land.

The soil was still red, showing between the concrete foundations of the bottling unit like dried blood on concrete.

A chain-link fence ran all the way around, the top carrying three strands of galvanized barbed wire that caught the glare of the morning sun.

Vikram sat in his brown leatherette chair.

It was no longer above the spare-parts godown.

Suresh had moved it to the new administrative wing, a room that smelled of fresh paint, synthetic floor glue, and the air conditioning that hummed from a white box on the wall.

He had tried to leave the chair behind.

"It looks bad, sir," Suresh had said. "The visitors from the state capital — they sit on the new leather. Then they see this."

"The visitors don't pay the loaders' wages," Vikram said.

"Still, sir."

"Leave it," Vikram said.

So the chair had stayed. The wheel that listed two degrees left made a dark, curved streak on the new grey linoleum floor.

---

From his window, Vikram could see the loading bay.

Twelve multi-axle trucks were lined up in the dust, their engines idling, the grey smoke rising straight in the windless heat.

The loaders were mostly local boys from the villages near the hills.

They wore faded blue shirts with the company logo printed on the pocket — a simple black malt grain.

A boy of about eighteen was sitting on a wooden crate near the rear tyre of the third truck, eating curd rice from a steel tiffin box.

His hands were white with the dust of the cement packing.

He used his fingers to scoop the rice quickly, looking at the security gate every few seconds as if he expected someone to tell him to move.

Vikram watched him.

He remembered table seven in the dissection hall.

He remembered the smell of formaldehyde.

A student who had wanted to know the names of the muscles in the arm so he could heal them.

Now, he knew the names of the load-unions. He knew how many bags of barley a truck could carry before the highway police demanded a bribe.

The boy near the truck finished his rice, closed the steel box, and wiped his fingers on the side of the wooden crate.

He stood up, adjusted his blue shirt, and went back to the loading ramp.

The signature of Ahuja Sahib on the clearance ledger had given that boy a tiffin box and a faded blue shirt.

It was a good thing.

But as Vikram watched the truck move slowly toward the gate, the dust rising to cover the red cotton fields, he felt only the weight of it.

The fourteen hundred crore was a number on a page.

The twelve acres was a map in the register.

But the text in the ledger didn't say how many more boys would have to spend their afternoons in the red Nandyal dust to make the numbers match.

[End of Part 10]
